Hi Judy,  Hope things are well with you and Peter in Georgia.
Until 5 days ago, I think there was more snow in Georgia than
on the Front Range of Colorado.  We've managed to get 6-8 inches
out at my house.

Just to update you on ARCMIP activities from our end.  We just received 
the first set of model data from John Cassano sending along ARCSyM
data.  We have done some homework on the EASE grid transforms and will 
start the conversion processing in the near future

I spoke to John at length about the data he is providing along with the
data that we might expect from other ARCMIP participants.  In the case 
of ARCSyM, the data are a 50 km resolution and John believes most others 
will be of similar spatial resolution.

 From your notes below, I understand that the CASPR/ISCCP satellite data 
are being converted to EASE at 25 km.  Now, back in Nov. you and I 
discussed this and the conclusion was that we should convert model 
output to EASE at 25 km.  However, John Cassano points out that going 
from 50 to 25 km for the model output really adds nothing to the 
dataset.  I just want to make sure about what resolution we want for the 
model output in EASE.  If we go with 25km resolution, do you recommend a 
preferred interpolation scheme to "fill" the data?

You should know that our plan is to coordinate our conversion work with 
the CASPR/ISCCP work being done by Math Rothstein at CU so that the 
generated model grids will overlay properly (e.g. model EASE grid point 
of origin and projection matches the  EASE grid for the CASPR data ). 
John Cassano will also help with this work.

I have CC'ed John C. and Math R. on this note in the hopes of reaching 
resolution that meets all requirements.  Guidance appreciated.

Have a good weekend,  Jim M
---------------------------------------------------------
Judith Curry wrote:
> Here are a few updates on arcmip.  From what I am hearing most of the 
> groups are making excellent progress towards completing their 
> simulations and getting them ready for JOSS.
> 
> The CASPR and ISCCP satellite data sets are almost finished in terms of 
> interpolating to ease grid, and comparison with sheba data is underway.  
> will keep  you posted on this.
> 
> The ARCMIP BAMS article is underway, hope to have a very rough draft out 
> for comments fairly soon
> 
> Colin has raised a few issues of relevance to the whole group.
> 
> For the 1D output at sheba grid pint, for the advective tendencies save  
> only the adiabatic tendencies, vertical and horizontal tendencies 
> separately.
> 
> For height of lowest cloud base, hugh morrison and matt shupe have been 
> using 10^-5 g m-3 as a threshold value in comparison of model with cloud 
> radar for sheba,  not terribly sensitive to the threshold value between 
> 10^-3 and 10^-7 g m^-3.  For those models allowing fraction, this is 
> less straightforward, because there are so many ways this can be handled 
> incl overlap issues, etc.  Would be open to anything that anyone has to 
> suggest here
> 
> Klaus reports that the new GLIMPSE homepage is at 
> http://www.awi-potsdam.de/www-pot/atmo/glimpse/index.html
> 
> As far as I know we are still on for the next ARCMIP workshop in in 
> Potsdam on 2 and 3 June 2003, in conjunction with the GLIMPSE meeting.  
> Definitely gives us a deadline for getting things done!
> 
> Judy
> 
> 
> 
> 



