>plotted that domain.txt file on a map or calculated its
>resolution from its data...
>
>
>But perhaps it is best to start at the beginning in defining your
>desired EASE-Grid. Following the EASE-Grid website, using the
>commonalities of what I've seen so far for ARCMIP:
>
>Map: that used by AVHRR (N200)
> Projection: azimuthal equal-area for the northern hemisphere
> Scale: 200 km/pixel (really 200.5402)
>Number grid cells per map unit: 4 for 50km, 8 for 25km
>
>After picking a resolution, do you want to pick a grid size,
>e.g. 70 columns, 55 rows or do you want to pick a certain
>area of the map (e.g. SHEBA domain)? Obviously 70x55 will
>cover different areas of the map depending on resolution,
>which is one of the things that has confused me thus far.
>
>Lastly is to locate the grid on the map, it appears a center
>of 72N, 153W is what you want.
>
>
>After fully defining the EASE-Grid being used, I'll need to know
>what kind of data filling/interpolation scheme I should use
>when re-gridding data. Particularly, how would I create 4 points
>of data in a 25km grid from 1 supplied point of 50km data?
>In the reverse case, any interpolation, weighted avgs, or just
>nearest neighbor?
>
>I hope all that made sense, or at least leads to things making sense.
>I'm new to EASE-Grid myself.
