> resolution from its data...

The infomation in the domain.txt file does correspond to a 50km resolution
polar stereographic map projection centered at 72N and 153W. From reading
the README file for CASPR ARCMIP data it seems to me that the CASPR
ARCMIP data has been subsampled from the original 25km resolution to
match the 50km ARCMIP domain resolution. I believe Randy Reeder was the
person that handled this conversion from the original AVHRR data to the
ARCMIP domain.

>
>
> But perhaps it is best to start at the beginning in defining your
> desired EASE-Grid. Following the EASE-Grid website, using the
> commonalities of what I've seen so far for ARCMIP:
>
> Map: that used by AVHRR (N200)
>  Projection: azimuthal equal-area for the northern hemisphere
>  Scale: 200 km/pixel (really 200.5402)
> Number grid cells per map unit: 4 for 50km, 8 for 25km
>
> After picking a resolution, do you want to pick a grid size,
> e.g. 70 columns, 55 rows or do you want to pick a certain
> area of the map (e.g. SHEBA domain)? Obviously 70x55 will
> cover different areas of the map depending on resolution,
> which is one of the things that has confused me thus far.
>
> Lastly is to locate the grid on the map, it appears a center
> of 72N, 153W is what you want.

I believe we were planning on using a 50km grid size for the ARCMIP
model output. This grid would be a subset of points from a 50km northern
hemisphere EASE grid (similar to the N200 projection described above,
except it would be an N50 project).

The grid should be centered at 72N and 153W and should encompass the entire
standard ARCMIP model domain (see the blue outline in the attached JPEG
file). Obviously the orientation of this ARCMIP model domain, relative
to the northern hemisphere EASE grid will require a bigger EASE grid
domain than just 70x55 grid points. I think the important point is
that the new ARCMIP EASE grid encompasses all of the standard ARCMIP
model domain grid points (and probably a slight buffer region beyond
this standard model domain to account for differences in model domains
between the different ARCMIP modeling groups).

The other very important point about the 50km EASE grid for the ARCMIP
model output is that the points in this domain should correspond to every
other point on Math Rothstein's 25km EASE grid for the ISCCP satellite data.
I believe he will be in contact shortly with the EASE grid map projection
information for his domain.

>
>
> After fully defining the EASE-Grid being used, I'll need to know
> what kind of data filling/interpolation scheme I should use
> when re-gridding data. Particularly, how would I create 4 points
> of data in a 25km grid from 1 supplied point of 50km data?
> In the reverse case, any interpolation, weighted avgs, or just
> nearest neighbor?
>

This won't be an issue since you will be using a 50km EASE grid with
50km model output.

I hope this helps.

Cheers,
John

