hi john...

it appears having everyone on a 50km grid is the desired goal...
i will reprocess the isccp data at this resolution and send it to 
you...the parameters are similar as the 25km grid i previously 
described and are as follows...

again it is a northern hemispheric ease grid, this time at 50km, making 
it a 361x361 square...it is "bore-centered" to the other ease grids (the 
12.5km and 25km described on nsidc's webpages)...i will be placing the 
isccp data (and randy the caspar data) on a subset of this grid starting 
at column 100, row 100 and which will comprise the inner-most 161x161 grid...

here is some c code i'll be using to conver from lat/lon to grid 
coordinates...i downloaded this code from nsidc's website and made 
just a few modifications (scale=0.5) to create the 50km grid...
remember to round the resulting grid coordinates up at .5 to get 
the integer row and column...

int ease_conv(double lat, double lon, double *r, double *s) {
   double Rg, phi, lam, rho, r0, s0, scale;
   int cols, rows;

   scale = 0.5;  /* 50km grid */

   cols = 721;
   rows = 721;

   /* radius of earth / nominal cell size */
   Rg = scale*6371.228/25.067525;

   r0 = (cols-1)/2. * scale;
   s0 = (rows-1)/2. * scale;

   /* degrees to radians */
   phi = lat*3.14159/180.0;
   lam = lon*3.14159/180.0;

   rho = 2 * Rg * sin(3.14159/4. - phi/2.);
   *r = r0 + rho * sin(lam);
   *s = s0 + rho * cos(lam);

   return(0);
 }


hope that helps...mathew 


