Subject: arcmip ease-grid questions
Status: RO

Hi all, I'm (finally) back working on the ARCMIP regridding
to the EASE-Grid. Sorry for the delay, but it is now my top
priority and I hope to finish soon. Although we have just 2
sets of model data here at JOSS (plus the CASPR and ISSCP
data which is now available for ordering).
There are a couple of open issues left over from our last
round of discussion, most importantly interpolation.

1. What should I do when more than one model point
falls into an EASE-Grid cell. For example, there are
327 EASE-Grid cells that contain 2 points from the
domain.txt file. (325 in the ARCSyM domain.nc)
Shall I average, some sort of weighted average,
take the point closest to center of the EASE-Grid cell, ... ?

2. fyi 37 of these duplicate cells have conflicting land uses.
If you would like to resolve this and produce a new domain.txt for
the EASE-Grid, somebody point me to a land use database and
conflict-resolution algorithm. I can then generate from the
EASE-Grid latlons directly.

3. fyi
I have put the EASE-Grid version of domain.txt on the web
for you to browse:

http://www.joss.ucar.edu/~john/tmp/ease_domain.txt

r=column, s=row for the EASE-Grid NL at 50km.
elat,elon are the centers of those grid cells.
Look at the bottom of the file to see some little stats,
incl the duplicates for land use clashes.

4. For the model data, I will leave "empty" cells in the new grid
as some sort of missing value, whatever the model already uses.

5. The EASE-Grid for domain.txt is 90x82. How much of a buffer
around this do you want (#cells, km, or degrees latlon) to
accomodate different models' edges? The latlons of the centers
of the corner cells are:
upper left   45.352936, -140.042451
upper right  53.890356,  159.954751
lower left   61.578634,  -83.558400
lower right  77.398961,   75.465545

6. Finally, fyi, a simple gif showing the grid bounds:

http://www.joss.ucar.edu/~john/tmp/ease_domain.gif

Thanks for your time,

John Allison
john@joss.ucar.edu

